# Practical Functional Programming and Clean Code

Canonical rules: **performance-architecture-standards.mdc** (KISS/YAGNI/DRY/SOLID/Self-Doc), **zustand-memo-optimization.mdc** (data-only stores, standalone setters), **api-response-processing.mdc** (guardWithTolerance always returns T), **generic.mdc** (self-doc, comments for "why" only).

## Key points
- **KISS/YAGNI/DRY:** See performance-architecture-standards.mdc.
- **Zustand:** Data-only stores; standalone setters; selective subscriptions (zustand-memo-optimization.mdc).
- **guardWithTolerance:** Always returns T; do not check null/undefined after (api-response-processing.mdc).
- **Type guards:** Prefer direct guard in condition; avoid redundant isDefined when guard handles it.

## Example: Type guard in condition (no redundant isDefined)
```typescript
// BAD - Redundant check when type guard handles undefined/null
if (!isDefined(response)) return;
if (isResponseDTO(response, { callbackOnError: debug, identifier: "ResponseDTO" })) { ... }

// GOOD - Let the type guard handle it
if (isResponseDTO(response, { callbackOnError: debug, identifier: "ResponseDTO" })) { ... }
```

## Example: Standalone setter in effect deps (minimal deps)
```typescript
// GOOD - setDataInStore is a standalone function; no store subscription, so deps stay minimal
useEffect(() => {
  if (isDefined(response)) setDataInStore(validatedData);
}, [response]);
```

